.TH LX 1 "July 2026" "lx 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lx \- view, navigate and filter log files in the terminal
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lx
[\fIoptions\fR] [\fIlogfile\fR]
.br
\fIproducer\fR |
.B lx
[\fIoptions\fR] [\fB\-\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lx
is an interactive, vi\-style viewer for log files (.log, .txt).
It parses each line against a
.I log template
that names the components of a log entry (timestamp, level, message, ...),
colours entries by severity, and lets you filter on any named field.
Lines that do not match the template (stack traces, wrapped output) are
treated as continuations of the previous entry and follow it through
filters.
.PP
Without
.B \-t
or
.B \-T
the template is auto\-detected from the file contents.
.PP
When no \fIlogfile\fR is given (or it is \fB\-\fR) and standard input is
not a terminal, the log is read from the pipe:
\fBjournalctl \-b | lx\fR, \fBlog show \-\-last 5m | lx\fR,
\fBdmesg | lx\fR. See
.BR "PIPED INPUT" .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-t " name"
Parse with the built\-in template \fIname\fR (see \fB\-l\fR).
.TP
.BI \-T " file"
Parse with a template definition loaded from \fIfile\fR (see
.BR "TEMPLATE FILES" ).
.TP
.BI \-g " file"
Interactively create a template for \fIlogfile\fR and write it to
\fIfile\fR (see
.BR "TEMPLATE WIZARD" ),
then offer to open the log with it.
.TP
.BI \-f " expr"
Apply the filter expression \fIexpr\fR at startup (see
.BR FILTERS ).
.TP
.B \-F
Start in follow mode: new data appended to the file appears
automatically, like
.BR "tail \-f" .
On Linux and macOS this uses inotify/kqueue; elsewhere the file is
polled.
.TP
.BI \-d " n"
In the entry inspector (\fBEnter\fR), show up to \fIn\fR wrapped lines
per field value. Without
.BR \-d ,
values are capped at 500 characters; longer values end with a note
saying how much was cut.
.TP
.B \-P
Non\-interactive mode: print the (filtered) lines to standard output and
exit. Useful in pipelines and scripts.
.TP
.BI \-e " name"
Export the built\-in template \fIname\fR as \fI.lxt\fR text to standard
output and exit \(em a convenient starting point for a custom template:
.B "lx \-e serilog > mine.lxt"
.TP
.B \-l
List the built\-in templates and exit.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show usage and exit.
.TP
.B \-V, \-\-version
Show the version and exit.
.SH BUILT-IN TEMPLATES
.TP
.B plain
Unstructured text; the whole line is the \fImessage\fR field.
.TP
.B syslog
BSD syslog / RFC 3164: \fIJun  1 19:18:23 host proc[42]: message\fR.
Fields: timestamp, host, proc, message.
.TP
.B syslog-iso
rsyslog with ISO timestamps:
\fI2026\-06\-01T19:18:23.123+02:00 host proc: message\fR.
.TP
.B dmesg
Linux kernel ring buffer: \fI[   12.345678] message\fR.
Fields: time (seconds since boot), message.
.TP
.B serilog
Serilog (.NET), both common shapes:
\fI2026\-07\-12 10:23:45.123 +02:00 [INF] message\fR and
\fI2026\-06\-01 19:18:23.123+2.00 UTC [INF]: message\fR.
Fields: timestamp, level (VRB DBG INF WRN ERR FTL), message.
.TP
.B python
Python logging:
\fI2026\-06\-01 19:18:23,123 \- logger \- INFO \- message\fR.
Fields: timestamp, logger, level, message.
.TP
.B macos
macOS unified log, as printed by
.B "log show"
or
.BR "log stream" :
\fI2026\-06\-01 19:18:23.123456+0200 0x16b3 Default 0x0 501 0 proc: message\fR.
Fields: timestamp, thread, type (Default Info Debug Error Fault),
activity, pid, ttl, process, message.
.TP
.B apache
Apache/nginx common log format. Fields: host, ident, user, timestamp,
request, status, size.
.SH KEY BINDINGS
.TP
.B j / k, arrow keys
Move the cursor down / up.
.TP
.B d / u  (also Ctrl\-D / Ctrl\-U)
Half a page down / up.
.TP
.B space / b, PageDown / PageUp
Full page down / up.
.TP
.B g / G, Home / End
Jump to the first / last entry.
.TP
.B h / l, left / right
Scroll horizontally; \fB0\fR resets.
.TP
.B Enter
Show the parsed fields of the current entry (name, type, unit, value).
Long values wrap across multiple lines, capped at 500 characters unless
.B \-d
raises the limit.
.TP
.B /
Search (case\-insensitive substring); \fBn\fR / \fBN\fR jump to the
next / previous match.
.TP
.B F
Toggle follow mode: the view sticks to the newest entry as data
arrives, like
.BR "tail \-f" .
Navigating away from the newest entry (k, PageUp, g, a search jump,
...) pauses follow so scrollback stays readable; press
.B F
again to resume. Without follow mode the view never moves on its own.
.TP
.BI : filter " expr"
Filter the entries (see
.BR FILTERS ).
.B :clear
removes the filter.
.TP
.BI : N
Go to line \fIN\fR.
.TP
.BI : template " name"
Re\-parse the file with another template (a built\-in name or a
\&.lxt file path).
.TP
.B ?
Help.
.TP
.B q
Quit.
.SH FILTERS
Filter expressions refer to the named fields of the active template:
.PP
.nf
    level == ERR
    level == ERR || level == WRN
    message ~ "connection timeout" && not level == DBG
    timestamp >= "2026-06-01 19:00:00" and timestamp < "2026-06-01 20:00"
    status >= 500
    proc ~ sshd
    raw ~ kernel          (raw: the whole unparsed line)
    line > 1000           (line: the line number)
.fi
.PP
Operators:
.B "== != ~ !~ > >= < <="
where
.B ~
means \fIcontains\fR (case\-insensitive). Boolean logic with
.B "&& || !"
or the words
.BR "and or not" ,
plus parentheses. Values may be barewords, quoted strings or numbers.
Comparisons use the field's declared type: numbers compare numerically,
timestamps chronologically by wall\-clock time as printed in the file
\(em never as strings (a value that cannot be parsed as a timestamp is
an error; only \fB~\fR/\fB!~\fR match the timestamp text).
.PP
Timestamp values are parsed with the template's own format first, then
common ISO/syslog forms, and understand two conveniences:
.TP
.B granularity
Equality covers the whole period the value names:
\fBtimestamp == "2026\-07\-13"\fR is that entire day,
\fB== "2026\-07\-13 09:15"\fR that minute,
\fB== "2026\-07\-13 09:15:02"\fR that second.
.TP
.B time of day
A value with a time but no date compares by clock time on any date:
\fBtimestamp >= "09:18:00"\fR, \fBtimestamp == "19:18"\fR.
.SH TEMPLATE FILES
A template file (conventionally \fI*.lxt\fR) describes the structure of
one log entry. Example:
.PP
.nf
    # MyApp logs look like:
    #   19:18:23.123 | WARN  | net | retry in 5 s
    name: myapp
    description: MyApp console output
    entry: %{time} | %{level} | %{module} | %{message}
    field time: type=timestamp format="%H:%M:%S.%f"
    field level: type=enum values=TRACE|DEBUG|INFO|WARN|ERROR
    field module: type=word
    field message: type=string
.fi
.PP
Ready\-made examples for every built\-in template live in
\fIdocumentation/examples/\fR, and
.B lx \-e
exports any built\-in as editable \fI.lxt\fR text.
.PP
A template may declare several
.B entry:
patterns (line\-shape variants, tried in order; the first match wins).
Each pattern mixes literal text with named
.B %{field}
placeholders. Every field can be declared with a
.B type
(string, word, int, float, timestamp, enum), a
.B unit
(informational, shown in the field inspector), allowed
.B values
(enums), a timestamp
.BR format ,
a display
.B color
(hex code), and
.B severity=yes
to mark it as the severity field. Field names become filter
identifiers. See
.I documentation/template\-format.md
for the full reference.
.SH COLORS
Each field can be given a colour with
.BI color= #RRGGBB
(also \fIRRGGBB\fR or \fI#RGB\fR); hex codes are mapped to the nearest
xterm\-256 colour, so they work in any 256\-colour terminal. All
built\-in templates ship with a default colour set. Severity overrides
field colours: error entries are tinted red and fatal entries bold red
across the whole line; on other entries the severity field is coloured
by its class (warning yellow, debug cyan, trace grey). Continuation
lines are dimmed.
.SH PIPED INPUT
With piped input the interactive viewer works as usual: the log data
comes from the pipe while the keyboard is read from the controlling
terminal. A stream that keeps producing (e.g.
.BR "journalctl \-f" ,
.BR "log stream" ,
.BR "dmesg \-w" )
keeps flowing into the viewer. The view only auto\-scrolls in follow
mode (press
.B F
or start with
.BR \-F ),
exactly like
.BR "tail \-f" ;
otherwise new entries accumulate without moving the view, and while
following, any manual navigation pauses the auto\-scroll until
.B F
is pressed again. When the producer closes the pipe, \fB(EOF)\fR
appears in the status bar. The template is
auto\-detected from the first burst of data unless \fB\-t\fR/\fB\-T\fR
is given.
.PP
Platform behaviour differs; explicitly:
.TP
.B Linux, macOS
Fully supported. The keyboard is re\-opened from \fI/dev/tty\fR, so a
controlling terminal is required: in environments without one (cron
jobs, detached daemons, CI) interactive mode cannot start \(em use
\fB\-P\fR there. New pipe data wakes the viewer immediately via
select(2).
.TP
.B Windows
The keyboard is re\-opened from \fICONIN$\fR. Console and pipe handles
cannot be waited on together here, so new pipe data is polled roughly
every 500 ms \(em streamed lines can appear with up to half a second of
delay. The Windows backend ships with the source but is not regularly
tested; treat it as best effort.
.TP
.B All platforms
\fB\-P\fR reads the pipe to end\-of\-stream before printing, like
grep(1); with a producer that never ends (\fBjournalctl \-f\fR) it will
run until interrupted. The template wizard (\fB\-g\fR) likewise
consumes the whole pipe before prompting, and cannot re\-open the
stream afterwards \(em it prints the matching \fBlx \-T\fR command to
run instead.
.SH TEMPLATE WIZARD
.B lx app.log \-g myapp.lxt
builds a template interactively, in the spirit of
.BR "git add \-p" :
every question shows its default in [brackets] and Enter accepts it.
The wizard picks a sample line from the log (you can choose another),
splits it into pieces using heuristics \(em timestamps (with a detected
format), severity keywords (offered as enums with a matching value
set), numbers, words, bracketed tokens, and a trailing free\-text
message \(em and then walks through each piece: name it, adjust its
type, format, values, unit and colour, answer '\-' to turn a piece into
literal text, or '*' to take everything from there to the end of the
line as one final field. Timestamp formats are validated against the
sample as you type them.
.PP
Before writing anything the wizard shows a colour preview of the sample
line, the full generated template, and how many lines of the log the
template actually matches. The written file is a normal \fI.lxt\fR you
can edit by hand afterwards.
.SH EXIT STATUS
0 on success, 1 on I/O errors, 2 on usage errors (bad option, unknown
template, invalid filter).
.SH EXAMPLES
A longer, runnable collection lives in
\fIdocumentation/usage.md\fR; sample logs for every built\-in template
are in \fIdocumentation/examples/\fR.
.SS Opening files
.TP
.B lx app.log
Open a log with template auto\-detection.
.TP
.B lx kern.log \-t dmesg
Parse with a named built\-in template (list them with \fBlx \-l\fR).
.TP
.B lx app.log \-T myapp.lxt \-f 'level==ERROR'
Custom template, pre\-filtered to errors.
.SS Pipes
.TP
.B journalctl \-b | lx
Browse this boot's systemd journal interactively.
.TP
.B log show \-\-last 1h | lx \-f 'type==Error || type==Fault'
The last hour of the macOS unified log, pre\-filtered.
.TP
.B docker logs api 2>&1 | lx
Container logs (merge stderr, since docker splits streams).
.TP
.B zcat /var/log/app.log.3.gz | lx
Rotated, compressed logs.
.TP
.B ssh web01 'journalctl \-u nginx \-n 5000' | lx
Remote logs over ssh.
.SS Following
.TP
.B lx service.log \-F
Follow a growing log file (like \fBtail \-f\fR).
.TP
.B journalctl \-f | lx \-F
Live\-follow a stream; navigation pauses the auto\-scroll, \fBF\fR
resumes it.
.SS Filtering and printing
.TP
.B lx access.log \-f 'status >= 500 || (status == 403 && request ~ admin)'
Boolean logic and numeric comparisons over named fields.
.TP
.B lx app.log \-f 'timestamp >= \(dq2026\-07\-13 09:00:00\(dq and level != DBG'
Wall\-clock timestamp range.
.TP
.B lx app.log \-P \-f 'level==ERR' > errors.txt
Print mode: lx as a structured grep.
.TP
.B journalctl \-b | lx \-P \-f 'message ~ oom' | wc \-l
Count matches from piped input in a pipeline.
.SS Templates
.TP
.B lx \-e serilog > mine.lxt
Export a built\-in template as editable \fI.lxt\fR text.
.TP
.B lx app.log \-g myapp.lxt
Create a template interactively with the wizard.
.TP
.B lx app.log \-d 20
Allow 20 wrapped lines per field value in the Enter inspector.
